recommendations.title: Extreme loneliness or the perfect balance? How to work from home and stay healthy
recommendations.excerpt: When Sean Blanda started working remotely in 2017, the allure of a “digital nomad” lifestyle – working at your laptop on the beach, say – wasn’t lost on him.

recommendations.title: The Most Powerful Activist in America Is Dying
recommendations.excerpt: The last few times Ady Barkan got arrested in the U.S. Capitol building, the routine had a few new twists. Officers no longer handcuffed him, since he had lost nearly all his capacity for movement. They just put a bracelet on one of his wrists to show he was in custody.

recommendations.title: Getting these 5 questions wrong can ruin your chances in a job interview
recommendations.excerpt: Making a good impression at a job interview involves a lot more than just dressing appropriately, being on time, and researching the company. Here are five key questions to answer for yourself if you want to make it to the next round.

recommendations.title: 7 Strange Questions That Help You Find Your Life Purpose
recommendations.excerpt: One day, when my brother was 18, he waltzed into the living room and proudly announced to my mother and me that one day he was going to be a senator. My mom probably gave him the “That’s nice, dear,” treatment while I’m sure I was distracted by a bowl of Cheerios or something.

recommendations.title: Physics Is Pointing Inexorably to Mind
recommendations.excerpt: In his 2014 book, Our Mathematical Universe, physicist Max Tegmark boldly claims that “protons, atoms, molecules, cells and stars” are all redundant “baggage.” Only the mathematical apparatus used to describe the behavior of matter is supposedly real, not matter itself.

recommendations.title: Adventurous. Alone. Attacked.
recommendations.excerpt: Carla Stefaniak did everything “right,” her best friend said. On a five-day vacation to Costa Rica in November to celebrate her 36th birthday, Ms. Stefaniak, a dual Venezuelan-American citizen, chose a gated Airbnb villa near the airport. It had a security guard. It was in a safe neighborhood.

recommendations.title: Your Smartphone Reduces Your Brainpower, Even If It's Just Sitting There
recommendations.excerpt: Even if a phone’s out of sight in a bag, even if it’s set to silent, even if it’s powered off, its mere presence will reduce someone’s working memory and problem-solving skills.

recommendations.title: Why the “velvet hammer” is a better way to give constructive criticism
recommendations.excerpt: It’s time to bag the sandwich method of delivering bad news. You know, the technique where you say something nice, then drop in the criticism, and the end with something nice.

recommendations.title: It’s Delightful, It’s Delicious, It’s DeVito
recommendations.excerpt: HOLLYWOOD — Danny DeVito has a spoon hanging off his nose. He’s trying to impress the beautiful woman having dinner at the next table at Craig’s, the Hollywood clubhouse. And it’s working. She’s cracking up.

recommendations.title: If you’re just not a morning person, science says you may never be
recommendations.excerpt: If Cassidy Sokolis ever needs to wake up before 11 am, she scatters three alarm clocks throughout her bedroom. Even then, she still often sleeps through the clamor. "It's really frustrating," Sokolis, a 21-year-old junior at Northern Arizona University, tells me.

recommendations.title: How to See if Someone is Tracking Emails They Send You
recommendations.excerpt: A few years ago a friend that works in PR told me about Streak, an email tracking service that lets you know when someone has opened a message you send them, sometimes with details about where that opening happened and even what device they were on when they were reading it.

recommendations.title: How Poor Americans Get Exploited by Their Landlords
recommendations.excerpt: Do the poor pay more for housing? That’s the question at the heart, and in the title, of a detailed paper published in the American Journal of Sociology on the actual housing costs paid by Americans in low-income urban neighborhoods.

recommendations.title: The Busier You Are, the More You Need Quiet Time
recommendations.excerpt: Real sustained silence, the kind that facilitates clear and creative thinking, quiets inner chatter as well as outer.

recommendations.title: How Bob's Red Mill Company Became A Gluten-Free Giant Ahead Of Its Time
recommendations.excerpt: Bob Moore, the 90-year-old founder of Bob's Red Mill, was just a few years into the business of milling whole grains at a converted animal feed mill in a Portland, Ore., suburb when he got a visit from some gluten-free Seattleites who had come down with a business proposition.

recommendations.title: Louisiana’s Disappearing Coast
recommendations.excerpt: The state loses a football field’s worth of land every hour and a half. Now engineers are in a race to prevent it from sinking into oblivion.

recommendations.title: How to Find New Music You'll Actually Like
recommendations.excerpt: Some people can dig up great music like magic, or have friends inside the industry who keep them updated. Some people are contented with their weekly Spotify Discover playlist.

recommendations.title: Scientists think they’ve solved one mystery of Easter Island’s statues
recommendations.excerpt: Chile's Easter Island (Rapa Nui) is famous for its giant monumental statues, called moai, built by early inhabitants some 800 years ago. The islanders likely chose the statues' locations based on the availability of fresh water sources, according to a recent paper in PLOS One.

recommendations.title: On the Trail of the Robocall King
recommendations.excerpt: Brad Young, a lawyer at TripAdvisor, arrived at the company’s offices in Needham, Massachusetts, on October 12, 2015, to find an email from his boss, Seth Kalvert, the company’s general counsel. In itself that wasn’t strange.

recommendations.title: 10 Small Habits That Have A Huge Return On Life
recommendations.excerpt: Don’t worry about how you will change. Focus on what habits you want to form and why.

recommendations.title: What If Instead of Taking the SAT You Got to Play a Video Game?
recommendations.excerpt: L.A.-based startup Imbellus plans to upset the SAT and ACT’s monopoly with a test it says accurately gauges critical thinking.
